# Visual Behavior Contract (Mandatory per Component Spec)

Migration exemption: see `AGENTS.md` § Migration Exemption (Phase 6–8).

## Hard Rules

- Every component spec must include a `## Visual Behavior Contract` with a behavior-to-CSS ownership matrix before implementation starts.
- No implementation may start without the matrix.

## Ownership Matrix columns (fixed)

| Behavior | Visual Geometry Owner | Stacking Context Owner | Interaction Hit-Area Owner | Selector(s) | Layer (z-index/token) | Test Oracle |

## Ownership Triad Rule

Every visual behavior has exactly three owners. Default: all three point to the same element.

| Owner | Responsible for | Forbidden from |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Geometry Owner | width, height, aspect-ratio, display | state classes, event bindings |
| State Owner | state class bindings (`[class.x]`) | geometry properties |
| Visual Owner | CSS rules (color, border, shadow, opacity, animation) | geometry of other elements |

Exceptions must be: (1) documented in spec table with reason, (2) solved via `position: absolute; inset: 0` relative to geometry owner, (3) never by duplicating geometry on multiple layers.

## Stacking context

Exactly one element per component declares `position: relative` — it owns the stacking context. Overlays use `position: absolute; inset: 0` relative to it.

## Layer Order

Define every layer explicitly. No undeclared z-index. Recommended: content → upload → selected → actions.

## State Ownership

Every visual state names its owner element and exact selector. See `docs/design/state-visuals.md` for canonical treatments — per-component ad-hoc treatments for shared semantic states are forbidden.

